# aiarch DESIGN workflow (TEMPLATE — server-committed, do not hand-edit in the user repo)
# =============================================================================
# This is a Go text/template. Its action delimiters are the double-square-bracket
# pair (not the default brace pair) — chosen so GitHub Actions' own ${{ ... }}
# expressions are left untouched. The server renders it with the
# configured GitHub App slug before seating it (renderDesignWorkflow); the ONLY
# templated value is the allowed_bots actor on the claude-code-action step.
#
# This is the DESIGN counterpart of the construction reference workflow
# (products/archistrator/deploy/construction-workflow/aiarch-construct.yml).
#
# Unlike the construction file (which the operator installs by hand into the
# construction repo), archistrator-server COMMITS THIS FILE into each user
# project repo at project birth, bundled with the go-test gate scaffold (go.mod +
# aiarch_method_test.go), via
#   sourceControlAccess.CommitManagedFiles(repo, ManagedScaffoldFiles(repo, slug), ...)
# (the C-PM-Δ caller threads the accessor), and KEEPS IT CURRENT after birth via the
# design Managers' MANAGED-SCAFFOLD SYNC: before every design-job dispatch the server
# re-renders this template and, when the seated copy drifted (e.g. the aiarch-state-mcp
# pin moved with a server release), commits the refreshed file to the default branch
# (sourcecontrol.SyncManagedScaffold — no drift, no commit). Hand-edits to the seated
# copy are therefore overwritten on the next dispatch. It then DISPATCHES it for every
# LLM-needing DESIGN activity (UC1 system-design + UC2 project-design drafting,
# PM-critique, redraft) via the SAME frozen verb construction uses —
# constructionPipelineAccess.SubmitConstructionPipeline (workflow_dispatch).
#
# The job runs claude-code-action on the USER'S CLAUDE_CODE_OAUTH_TOKEN + the
# user's CI minutes. aiarch holds NO LLM key and makes NO synchronous LLM call.
# The action drafts the typed Method artifact per the supplied PROMPT and commits
# the resulting JSON under .aiarch/state/ (the exact path the `validate` gate and
# projectStateAccess read).
#
# WHETHER A PR IS OPENED DEPENDS ON job_mode (F39 rail-debris fix):
#   - job_mode=draft: the action ALSO opens a PR so the human review gate + the
#     required `validate` check apply to the drafted model. A red validate check
#     BLOCKS merge — that red check IS the trust boundary (C-VCI).
#   - job_mode=critique: the action does NOT open a PR. The Manager reads the
#     committed `critiqueVerdict` STRAIGHT OFF the branch; a critique PR is never
#     merged (by design) and would accumulate as abandoned rail debris (F39). The
#     verdict is committed to the branch and the guard below proves the branch
#     advanced — no PR, no merge gate, is involved on the critique path.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# LOAD-BEARING DISPATCH CONTRACT — DO NOT CHANGE THESE ANCHORS:
#
#   1. workflow_dispatch input named EXACTLY `idempotency_token` (string,
#      required). Constant: framework-go-infrastructure-github
#      DispatchInputKeyIdempotency = "idempotency_token". The
#      constructionPipelineAccess RA fills it and finds/dedups/observes/cancels
#      runs BY RUN NAME.
#
#   2. Top-level `run-name: aiarch-cp-${{ inputs.idempotency_token }}`. The
#      prefix `aiarch-cp-` is the RA's RunNamePrefix; ListRunsByName matches
#      RunNamePrefix+token. If this run-name is wrong, dispatch idempotency,
#      observe, and cancel ALL silently break (the RA dispatches runs it can
#      never see) — identical failure mode to the construction workflow.
#
#   3. The workflow MUST be `workflow_dispatch`-triggerable on the dispatch ref.
#
# The DESIGN-job inputs (`artifact_kind`, `command`, `target_branch`,
# `prior_state_ref`, `job_mode`) are the additive DispatchInputs the design Managers
# (C-MSD-Δ / C-MPD-Δ) set on PipelineSpec. Their NAMES are a contract between
# this file and those Managers — see designs/aiarch/implementation/log/C-WF-DESIGN.md.
#
# job_mode (D-MSD-Δ amendment) discriminates a DRAFT job from a PM-CRITIQUE job:
#   - "draft"    (default): the action drafts the typed `artifact_kind` model and
#                commits it as the slot's `model` in .aiarch/state/project.json.
#   - "critique": the action does NOT rewrite the model. It records its verdict into
#                the SAME slot's first-class critique carrier — `critiqueVerdict`
#                (exactly "approve" or "revise") and, on "revise", `critiqueNotes`
#                (the revision guidance) — which the Manager reads back. The action
#                MUST commit a non-empty `critiqueVerdict` and MUST NOT touch the
#                slot's `notes` (the architect's reject/withdraw rationale). The exact
#                JSON shape is spelled out in the critique command; this flag
#                steers BOTH the template's commit-target instruction AND whether a PR
#                is opened: a critique job commits to the branch and does NOT open a PR
#                (the Manager reads `critiqueVerdict` off the branch; a critique PR is
#                never merged and would pile up as abandoned rail debris — F39).
#
# REQUIRED CHECK — `aiarch-state-mcp validate`:
#   The `validate` job (the job NAME is the branch-protection anchor — do not rename)
#   installs the SAME pinned aiarch-state-mcp binary the draft job uses and runs its
#   `validate` subcommand over the checked-out repo: the identical methodcheck
#   design-JSON rules the old seated `go test` gate ran (and putDraftModel enforces
#   in-loop), PLUS the STALENESS-AWARE cross-artifact severity policy — a
#   System×OperationalConcepts join rule (DEP-COVERAGE / DEP-GRAPH-IDENTITY /
#   DEP-MEMBER-EXIST and siblings) downgrades from Error to Warning while the
#   OperationalConcepts slot is flagged StaleBasis (its reconciliation is pending BY
#   DESIGN after an upstream amendment), so a cross-artifact amendment no longer
#   deadlocks the rail. Sealing the phase unreconciled stays impossible via the
#   server's STALE-UNACKED AdvancePhase gate. A non-zero exit (surviving
#   Error-severity findings) BLOCKS PR merge — that red check IS the trust boundary.
#   WHY THE BINARY AND NOT THE SEATED `go test`: the enforcement stack must be
#   SELF-UPDATING — the binary ships the whole app-side rule stack at the pin this
#   file installs, and the managed-scaffold sync refreshes this file whenever the pin
#   moves; the seated go.mod route needed a platform release + a product go.mod bump
#   per rule change (the drift class the sync exists to kill). The seated scaffold
#   (go.mod + aiarch_method_test.go) REMAINS for the product repo's own CI once it
#   has Go code: the arch layer rules + design↔code alignment need go/packages over
#   the product module, which an installed binary cannot run.
# =============================================================================

name: aiarch-design

# (2) Run-name is the idempotency anchor the RA resolves runs by. EXACT prefix.
run-name: aiarch-cp-${{ inputs.idempotency_token }}

on:
  workflow_dispatch:
    inputs:
      # (1) LOAD-BEARING — the dedup token the RA stamps into run-name above.
      idempotency_token:
        description: "aiarch dedup token (RA-supplied; stamped into run-name)"
        required: true
        type: string
      # --- DESIGN-job parameters (DispatchInputs; set by C-MSD-Δ / C-MPD-Δ) ---
      # The typed Method artifact KIND the action must draft+commit (e.g.
      # "Mission", "Glossary", "Volatilities", "CoreUseCases", "System",
      # "OperationalConcepts", "StandardCheck"; UC2 plan kinds analogously).
      artifact_kind:
        description: "typed Method artifact kind to draft (e.g. Mission, Volatilities)"
        required: true
        type: string
      # Thin routing: the slash command this design job runs (e.g. mission-draft).
      # The command (under .claude/commands/) carries its role agent + Method skill +
      # the-method-project-state — the drafting logic lives there, not in this file.
      # The Manager computed it from artifact_kind + job_mode.
      command:
        description: "slash command for this design job"
        required: true
        type: string
      # The branch the action commits the drafted JSON onto and opens the PR from.
      # The Manager owns branch naming (branch-per-activity, +1 relay).
      target_branch:
        description: "branch to draft onto and open the design PR from"
        required: true
        type: string
      # Pointer to the prior committed project state the draft builds on — the
      # git ref (commit SHA or branch) whose .aiarch/state/project.json the action
      # reads as input context. Empty on the first artifact of a fresh project.
      prior_state_ref:
        description: "git ref of prior committed .aiarch/state to build the draft on"
        required: false
        type: string
        default: ""
      # DRAFT vs PM-CRITIQUE vs ANSWER discriminator (D-MSD-Δ + question-comments).
      # "draft" (default) commits the typed model; "critique" commits the slot's
      # critiqueVerdict/critiqueNotes read-back carrier; "answer" (question-comments)
      # commits per-question responses into the slot's reviewThread via
      # respondToReviewComment (no model rewrite, no verdict). Only "draft" opens a PR;
      # critique and answer commit to the branch and the Manager reads back off it.
      # Defaulted so a dispatch that omits it behaves exactly as a draft.
      job_mode:
        description: "draft (commit the typed model), critique (commit critiqueVerdict/critiqueNotes), or answer (commit review-comment responses)"
        required: false
        type: string
        default: "draft"

# The action drafts and commits the typed JSON and opens a PR, so it needs to
# write repo contents and pull requests. The LLM call is authenticated by the
# CLAUDE_CODE_OAUTH_TOKEN repo Actions secret, which is provisioned by the Claude
# Code GitHub App when the user runs /install-github-app (aiarch does no secret
# management), NOT by this in-run GITHUB_TOKEN.
# id-token is required by claude-code-action's OIDC exchange (it mints its
# GitHub credential via the Claude GitHub App when no github_token input is
# supplied) — same grant as the reference aiarch-construct.yml. Observed live
# 2026-07-04: without it the draft job dies at "Failed to get OIDC token".
permissions:
  contents: write
  pull-requests: write
  id-token: write

# One in-flight design run per dedup token — belt-and-braces alongside the RA's
# own run-name convergence (identical to construction).
concurrency:
  group: aiarch-cp-${{ inputs.idempotency_token }}
  cancel-in-progress: false

jobs:
  # ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
  # draft — run claude-code-action on the USER's CLAUDE_CODE_OAUTH_TOKEN to draft
  # the typed Method artifact per the command and COMMIT the resulting JSON
  # under .aiarch/state/ on target_branch, then open a PR. The action holds the
  # LLM credential; aiarch never does.
  # ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
  draft:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - name: Checkout prior committed state
        uses: actions/checkout@v4
        with:
          # Build the draft on the prior committed state when supplied; otherwise
          # the workflow ref (a fresh project).
          ref: ${{ inputs.prior_state_ref != '' && inputs.prior_state_ref || github.ref }}
          fetch-depth: 0

      # -----------------------------------------------------------------------
      # aiarch-state MCP server (agentic-managers spec §Construction application).
      # The drafting agent NO LONGER hand-edits .aiarch/state/project.json or runs git:
      # it authors the typed Method artifact through the "aiarch-state" MCP tools, which
      # ARE ProjectStateAccess code operating on this checkout. putDraftModel validates
      # every model through the FULL projectstate codec + methodcheck BEFORE writing (so a
      # bad enum / missing id is rejected in-loop with an actionable error, not committed
      # to stall the rail), and publishDraft is the single, exactly-once commit+push.
      #
      # It is installed BEFORE the refresh step because the refresh's deterministic
      # conflict RESOLVER (F80) invokes this same binary's `reconcile` subcommand — keeping
      # ALL state-file logic in ProjectStateAccess code rather than a bash/jq hack.
      #
      # DELIVERY: the binary is obtained the SAME way the seated go.mod scaffold obtains
      # framework-go — `go install <module>@<pin>` resolved via GOPROXY (a published
      # module) — so it carries the identical trust/access profile as today's platform
      # module fetch. The binary lives in the archistrator SERVER module because it must
      # reuse the STRICT projectstate codec in server/internal (a package only that module
      # can import). Requires the archistrator repo to be resolvable by GOPROXY (public);
      # until then this step fails RED, the correct visible signal.
      # -----------------------------------------------------------------------
      - name: Set up Go (for the aiarch-state MCP server)
        uses: actions/setup-go@v5
        with:
          # Pin the toolchain INDEPENDENTLY of the seated go.mod (which tracks the user
          # module / framework-go). `go install` of the archistrator SERVER module needs a
          # Go at least as new as that module's own `go` directive, so pin the latest 1.25
          # patch here rather than inheriting the user repo's (possibly older) go-version.
          go-version: "1.25.x"

      - name: Obtain the aiarch-state MCP server
        id: statemcp
        env:
          GOBIN: ${{ runner.temp }}/aiarch-bin
          # VERSION HANDSHAKE (managed-scaffold sync): the control plane stamps the
          # state-MCP pin it rendered this seated file with; the job echoes it so any
          # run's log states which binary generation this scaffold carries. The server's
          # sync-on-dispatch refreshes this whole file whenever its own pin moves, so a
          # run can never install a binary the dispatching server's validators reject.
          AIARCH_STATE_MCP_PIN: "[[.StateMcpModuleVersion]]"
        run: |
          echo "aiarch-state-mcp pin: [[.StateMcpModulePath]]@${AIARCH_STATE_MCP_PIN}"
          mkdir -p "${GOBIN}"
          go install [[.StateMcpModulePath]]@"${AIARCH_STATE_MCP_PIN}"
          echo "bin=${GOBIN}/aiarch-state-mcp" >> "$GITHUB_OUTPUT"

      # REFRESH-FROM-MAIN (F40 founder ruling 2026-07-05; F80 reconcile 2026-07-05). One
      # persistent session branch per artifact accumulates every draft/critique/redraft
      # until it merges (not a branch-per-attempt). The stale-base problem the old
      # branch-per-retry topology solved (a branch cut from main BEFORE a main-side fix
      # landed — e.g. the internal/scaffold fix — whose required `validate` gate then fails
      # forever) is handled HERE instead: before every DRAFT/CRITIQUE job we re-merge
      # origin/main into the session branch so it (and its CI base) always picks up
      # main-side fixes.
      #
      # F80(a): ANSWER jobs are EXEMPT from the merge-from-main — they only append
      # per-question responses onto the branch tip's review ledger, never touch the model,
      # and must not risk a merge conflict (the live failure: an answer job died refreshing
      # from main). They STILL check out the session-branch tip (the append target) but
      # short-circuit before the merge. Draft/critique jobs merge main as before.
      #
      # F80(b): project.json is a SERVER-OWNED, SINGLE-WRITER-PER-SLOT document, so a
      # main-side advance (a staleness ack, a question seed) legitimately collides with the
      # in-flight draft on that one file. Rather than dead-ending RED, a conflict is
      # resolved DETERMINISTICALLY by `aiarch-state-mcp reconcile` — main's document with
      # THIS session's own slot overlaid — and the resolution is committed to complete the
      # merge. The push uses the run's own GITHUB_TOKEN.
      #
      # F82: a conflict the reconcile CANNOT resolve does not dead-end the refresh either. A
      # design session branch is machine-generated scratch; the durable committed state lives
      # on main. A conflict that reconcile rejects (e.g. a WITHDRAWN draft whose session
      # branch survived — rail branch cleanup is platform-gated future work) or a conflict on
      # ANY file OTHER than the owned state slot means the branch carries DEAD content that
      # would otherwise brick every future amendment of the slot. So the refresh self-heals:
      # abort the merge, hard-reset the session branch to origin/main, force-push (with lease),
      # and emit a ::notice. The active-draft reconcile path (F80b) is unchanged and still
      # wins whenever the branch's own slot is recoverable, so live reviews are never reset.
      - name: Refresh the session branch from main
        env:
          JOB_MODE: ${{ inputs.job_mode }}
          TARGET_BRANCH: ${{ inputs.target_branch }}
          ARTIFACT_KIND: ${{ inputs.artifact_kind }}
          PROJECT_ID: ${{ github.event.repository.name }}
          STATE_MCP: ${{ steps.statemcp.outputs.bin }}
          STATE_FILE: .aiarch/state/project.json
        run: |
          git config user.name "github-actions[bot]"
          git config user.email "github-actions[bot]@users.noreply.github.com"
          git fetch --no-tags origin main "${TARGET_BRANCH}"
          git checkout -B "${TARGET_BRANCH}" "origin/${TARGET_BRANCH}"
          if [ "${JOB_MODE}" = "answer" ]; then
            echo "answer job: on the session-branch tip, skipping merge-from-main (F80a)"
            exit 0
          fi
          if git merge --no-edit origin/main; then
            git push origin "HEAD:${TARGET_BRANCH}"
            exit 0
          fi
          # F82: self-heal a conflicting refresh. The session branch is machine-generated
          # scratch; the durable committed state lives on main. When the branch carries dead
          # content that cannot be reconciled (a withdrawn/abandoned draft whose branch
          # survived, or a conflict on any file beyond the owned state slot), abort the merge,
          # hard-reset the branch to origin/main, and force-push so this amendment builds on
          # the committed state instead of dead-ending every future amendment of the slot.
          self_heal_reset() {
            git merge --abort || true
            git reset --hard origin/main
            git push --force-with-lease origin "HEAD:${TARGET_BRANCH}"
            echo "::notice::conflicting refresh — the session branch carried dead draft content (${1:-diverged from main}); hard-reset ${TARGET_BRANCH} to origin/main so this amendment builds on the committed state. A withdrawn/abandoned draft on the old branch is discarded (rail branch cleanup is platform-gated future work)."
          }
          # A conflict on ANY file OTHER than the owned state slot means the branch is corrupt
          # scratch (it should only ever write state) — self-heal rather than dead-end.
          conflicts="$(git diff --name-only --diff-filter=U)"
          if [ "${conflicts}" != "${STATE_FILE}" ]; then
            self_heal_reset "conflict on files beyond the owned state slot (${conflicts})"
            exit 0
          fi
          # F80(b) ACTIVE-draft path: main advanced another slot while this draft is
          # AwaitingReview. Overlay THIS session's own slot onto main deterministically; the
          # in-flight draft + its review ledger survive. This wins whenever the branch's own
          # slot is recoverable, so a live review is never reset.
          echo "reconciling ${STATE_FILE}: main + this session's own slot (${ARTIFACT_KIND})"
          git show ":3:${STATE_FILE}" > "${RUNNER_TEMP}/main-project.json"   # theirs = origin/main
          git show ":2:${STATE_FILE}" > "${RUNNER_TEMP}/ours-project.json"   # ours   = session branch
          if AIARCH_PROJECT_ID="${PROJECT_ID}" AIARCH_ARTIFACT_KIND="${ARTIFACT_KIND}" \
            "${STATE_MCP}" reconcile \
              --base "${RUNNER_TEMP}/main-project.json" \
              --ours "${RUNNER_TEMP}/ours-project.json" \
              --out "${STATE_FILE}"; then
            git add "${STATE_FILE}"
            git commit --no-edit
            git push origin "HEAD:${TARGET_BRANCH}"
            exit 0
          fi
          # F82: reconcile rejected the branch's own slot (unrecoverable — e.g. a withdrawn
          # draft that fails the required-field gate). Treat the branch as dead scratch.
          self_heal_reset "state slot could not be reconciled (stale/withdrawn draft)"

      # Record the base commit the draft is built on — the REFRESHED session-branch tip (so
      # the post-claude guard measures whether CLAUDE advanced the branch beyond the refresh,
      # not the refresh merge itself). See "Verify claude pushed a commit".
      - name: Record base SHA
        id: base
        run: echo "sha=$(git rev-parse HEAD)" >> "$GITHUB_OUTPUT"

      # The MCP config claude-code-action passes to the Claude CLI (--mcp-config). The
      # ambient session context is baked in as env on the MCP server process from the
      # dispatch inputs + the per-project repo name (project id = repo name). The agent
      # supplies NONE of these — the ambient artifact_kind fixes the slot, so it can never
      # infer the wrong one (the F68 fix, made structural).
      - name: Write the aiarch-state MCP config
        env:
          MCP_BIN: ${{ steps.statemcp.outputs.bin }}
        run: |
          cat > "${RUNNER_TEMP}/aiarch-mcp.json" <<EOF
          {
            "mcpServers": {
              "aiarch-state": {
                "command": "${MCP_BIN}",
                "env": {
                  "AIARCH_PROJECT_ID": "${{ github.event.repository.name }}",
                  "AIARCH_ARTIFACT_KIND": "${{ inputs.artifact_kind }}",
                  "AIARCH_JOB_MODE": "${{ inputs.job_mode }}",
                  "AIARCH_TARGET_BRANCH": "${{ inputs.target_branch }}",
                  "AIARCH_STATE_ROOT": "${{ github.workspace }}"
                }
              }
            }
          }
          EOF

      - name: Draft the typed Method artifact (claude-code-action)
        uses: anthropics/claude-code-action@v1
        with:
          # The user's OAuth token, provisioned as a repo Actions secret by the
          # Claude Code GitHub App (/install-github-app). NAME-only reference —
          # aiarch never mints or sees this value.
          claude_code_oauth_token: ${{ secrets.CLAUDE_CODE_OAUTH_TOKEN }}
          [[- if .AppSlug ]]
          # The DESIGN workflow is ALWAYS workflow_dispatch'ed by the aiarch GitHub
          # App (a Bot actor); claude-code-action refuses bot-initiated runs unless
          # the bot is allow-listed (observed live: run 28723145540 failed with
          # "Workflow initiated by non-human actor: <app> (type: Bot). Add bot to
          # allowed_bots list"). Mirrors aiarch-construct.yml's allowed_bots. The App
          # slug varies per deployment, so the SERVER templates it here; when it is
          # unconfigured this line is omitted entirely, leaving human-dispatched runs
          # working.
          allowed_bots: [[.AppSlug]]
          [[- end ]]
          # Autonomous CI: the runner is an ephemeral container scoped to this one
          # design task, with NO human present to approve claude-code-action's
          # interactive permission prompts. Without this flag, every file-write / git /
          # gh tool call defaults to prompting and is AUTO-DENIED in CI — observed live
          # 2026-07-04 (gtdapp run 28724066929: 53 permission_denials, 70 turns, nothing
          # committed, no PR — yet the action still exited success). Skip the prompts so
          # claude can write the JSON, commit, and open the PR unattended. This is the
          # SAME grant the construction reference workflow uses (aiarch-construct.yml).
          # The trust boundary is NOT the tool prompt: it is the branch + PR human gate
          # plus the REQUIRED `validate` (methodcheck) check that blocks merge (C-VCI).
          # --mcp-config wires the local aiarch-state MCP server (installed above) into the
          # Claude CLI. --dangerously-skip-permissions auto-allows tool calls (incl. the MCP
          # tools) in the unattended runner — the trust boundary is NOT the tool prompt: it is
          # putDraftModel's in-loop codec+methodcheck validation, the branch + PR human gate,
          # and the REQUIRED `validate` (methodcheck) check that blocks merge (C-VCI).
          claude_args: "--dangerously-skip-permissions --mcp-config ${{ runner.temp }}/aiarch-mcp.json"
          # Thin prompt: NO drafting logic here. The intent lives entirely in the
          # per-kind design command under .claude/commands/, which pulls its role
          # agent + Method skill + the-method-project-state (the doctrine that ALL
          # reads/writes go through the "aiarch-state" MCP tools, that publishDraft is
          # the last call, and that no PR is opened by the agent). The Manager computed
          # `command`; the workflow just runs it against the ambient design job.
          prompt: |
            /${{ inputs.command }}

      # Silent-failure guard. claude-code-action can exit SUCCESS while committing
      # nothing (observed live 2026-07-04, run 28724066929: draft job green, zero
      # commits, no PR — the Manager's observe loop only ever saw the validate failure).
      # This step turns "claude did nothing" into a RED run: it fails when the target
      # branch is missing on the remote, or when it still points at the base SHA (no new
      # commit). Deterministic: one ref lookup + string compare, no heuristics.
      # MUST read the ref via the REST API with the run's own github.token — NOT
      # `git ls-remote origin`: claude-code-action rewrites origin's URL to embed its
      # app token for the push, then REVOKES that token in its cleanup, so any later
      # git operation against origin fails auth (observed live 2026-07-05, run
      # 28724503360: guard false-negatived a successful draft+PR).
      # POSIX single-bracket tests only — the bash double-bracket test would collide
      # with the Go-template action delimiters this file is rendered through.
      - name: Verify claude pushed a commit to the target branch
        if: always()
        env:
          TARGET_BRANCH: ${{ inputs.target_branch }}
          BASE_SHA: ${{ steps.base.outputs.sha }}
          GH_TOKEN: ${{ github.token }}
        run: |
          remote_sha="$(gh api "repos/${GITHUB_REPOSITORY}/git/ref/heads/${TARGET_BRANCH}" --jq .object.sha 2>/dev/null || true)"
          if [ -z "$remote_sha" ]; then
            echo "::error::claude-code-action exited without pushing branch '${TARGET_BRANCH}' — no commit, no PR. Treating the green claude step as a failed draft."
            exit 1
          fi
          if [ "$remote_sha" = "$BASE_SHA" ]; then
            echo "::error::branch '${TARGET_BRANCH}' is unchanged from base ${BASE_SHA} — claude committed nothing. Treating the green claude step as a failed draft."
            exit 1
          fi
          echo "branch '${TARGET_BRANCH}' advanced ${BASE_SHA} -> ${remote_sha}"

  # ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
  # validate — REQUIRED status check (the JOB NAME is the branch-protection anchor —
  # do not rename). Installs the SAME pinned aiarch-state-mcp binary the draft job
  # uses and runs `aiarch-state-mcp validate` over the checked-out branch: the strict
  # server-codec decode of .aiarch/state/project.json (read-back parity) + the
  # identical methodcheck design rules putDraftModel enforces in-loop, under the GATE
  # SEVERITY POLICIES (the amendment-deadlock fixes, 2026-07-06): STALENESS-AWARE
  # cross-artifact severity (System×OperationalConcepts join rules are advisory while
  # the OperationalConcepts slot is flagged StaleBasis — reconciliation pending by
  # design) and SLOT-SCOPED severity (`--slot` threads this job's ambient artifact —
  # the same dispatch input that fixes the drafting agent's slot — so errors
  # attributed to OTHER slots, pre-existing committed data this session cannot write,
  # downgrade to annotated warnings; only ambient-slot and structural findings
  # block). A non-zero exit (surviving Error findings) BLOCKS merge — the trust
  # boundary. This REPLACED the seated go-test steps (tidy + test over the seated
  # scaffold) so the gate self-updates with the state-MCP pin (managed-scaffold sync)
  # instead of requiring a platform release + product go.mod bump per rule change;
  # the seated go.mod / aiarch_method_test.go scaffold remains for the product
  # repo's own CI (arch layer rules + design↔code alignment over product Go code,
  # which an installed binary cannot run).
  # ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
  validate:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    needs: draft
    steps:
      - name: Checkout drafted state
        uses: actions/checkout@v4
        with:
          ref: ${{ inputs.target_branch }}

      - name: Set up Go (for the aiarch-state validator)
        uses: actions/setup-go@v5
        with:
          # Pin the toolchain INDEPENDENTLY of the seated go.mod: `go install` of the
          # archistrator SERVER module needs a Go at least as new as that module's own
          # `go` directive — same rationale as the draft job's setup-go step.
          go-version: "1.25.x"

      - name: Obtain the aiarch-state validator
        id: statemcp
        env:
          GOBIN: ${{ runner.temp }}/aiarch-bin
          # VERSION HANDSHAKE (managed-scaffold sync): same pin as the draft job's
          # install — the validator that gates the PR is BY CONSTRUCTION the same
          # binary generation that authored/validated the draft in-loop, so the two
          # verdicts can never disagree.
          AIARCH_STATE_MCP_PIN: "[[.StateMcpModuleVersion]]"
        run: |
          echo "aiarch-state-mcp pin: [[.StateMcpModulePath]]@${AIARCH_STATE_MCP_PIN}"
          mkdir -p "${GOBIN}"
          go install [[.StateMcpModulePath]]@"${AIARCH_STATE_MCP_PIN}"
          echo "bin=${GOBIN}/aiarch-state-mcp" >> "$GITHUB_OUTPUT"

      - name: aiarch-state validate (Method-invariant required check)
        # Runs the policy-aware Method gate over ./.aiarch/state/project.json. A
        # non-zero exit (surviving Error-severity findings, or a state document the
        # strict server codec rejects) BLOCKS PR merge. The gate log carries every
        # finding (rule id, severity, message) including the downgraded-to-warning
        # findings with their staleness / slot-scope rationale. --slot receives the
        # job's ambient artifact from the SAME dispatch input the draft job's MCP env
        # fixes the agent's slot with (threaded via env, never shell-interpolated), so
        # the in-loop putDraftModel verdict and this CI verdict scope identically.
        env:
          ARTIFACT_KIND: ${{ inputs.artifact_kind }}
        run: ${{ steps.statemcp.outputs.bin }} validate --slot "${ARTIFACT_KIND}"
